sentences: Robert Lawrence Welch Jr. (August 31, 1945 – June 7, 2012) was an American musician who was a member of Fleetwood Mac from 1971 to 1974.
Robert Lawrence Welch Jr. (August 31, 1945 – June 7, 2012) was an American musician who was a member of Fleetwood Mac from 1971 to 1974.
He had a successful solo career in the late 1970s.
Welch Sr. produced the 25th Annual Academy Awards TV special in 1953 and The Thin Man TV series from 1958 to 1959.

In 1964, Welch joined the Los Angeles-based vocal group The Seven Souls as a guitarist.
The Seven Souls' 1967 single "I'm No Stranger" made no impact at the time of its release, despite subsequent issue in France and Italy.
The Seven Souls broke up in 1969.
He later told People that his time in Paris (1969-1971) was "living on rice and beans and sleeping on the floor."
In 1971, Welch auditioned for Fleetwood Mac at Kiln House, their retreat in England.
The band had recently lost one of its front-line members, guitarist Jeremy Spencer, and were looking for a replacement.
The band had a few meetings with Welch and decided to hire him, despite not having previously played with him, after listening to some of his songs on tape.
The band's first album to feature Christine McVie and Welch, Future Games, was recorded at Advision Studios in London (as is cited on the back of the album jacket).
In September 1971 the band released Future Games, with the title song written by Welch.

sentences: In 1975, Welch formed the short-lived hard rock power trio Paris with ex-Jethro Tull bassist Glenn Cornick and former Nazz drummer Thom Mooney.
Paris released two commercially unsuccessful albums: Paris and Big Towne, 2061.
In a 1979 interview with People, Welch said that the two Paris albums were "ill-conceived."
Mick Fleetwood managed Welch's career into the 1980s.
During the height of their respective popularity in the late 1970s, Welch frequently opened for Fleetwood Mac and would sit in as lead vocalist on "Hypnotized".
In September 1977, Welch released his first solo album, French Kiss, a mainstream pop collection featuring contributions from Fleetwood, Buckingham and Christine McVie.
The album was certified platinum by the RIAA, peaking at #12 on the Billboard chart in 1978.
Welch followed up French Kiss with two albums in 1979.

In February, Three Hearts, an album that replicated the rock/disco fusion of French Kiss, peaked at #20 (earning a RIAA gold certification) and spawned the hit "Precious Love" (#19), while the follow-up single "Church" (#73) also charted.
His second effort that year, November's "The Other One", saw Bob's first solo recordings without the help of any Fleetwood Mac members.

From 1980 to 1981, he hosted Hollywood Heartbeat, an early music video program.
His subsequent solo albums into the early 1980s (Man Overboard, Bob Welch, and Eye Contact) were not successful and his career declined.
